pr_review_comment_body:
In my code above, "Iterator" is just the "T" of the template. I could have called it "InputIterator42" or "George".

To write this method, you don't have to know anything about iterators. Just write it as if they're pointers.

~~~c++
for(Iterator it = initialData_begin; it != initialData_end; ++it)
{
  append(*it);
}
~~~

Separately, you could choose to make the MovingWindow iterable, but that's a separate feature. You could create a nested class `MovingWindow::Iterator` and add `begin` and `end` methods to the `MovingWindow`, but that's optional. To do this, you don't need to know anything about `std::iterator`, you just need to implement a few public methods. You can see an example where I did this here: https://github.com/numenta/nupic.core/blob/b83798346e85bdbf773652c7597f00a4a9ed6575/src/nupic/utils/GroupBy.hpp#L93 (though these classes are kinda complicated)

This `local_repodata` is already going to have `_mod` and `_etag` keys.  As an extra level of caution, I'd propose passing those values through as arguments to this function, and then to `read_pickled_repodata`, so on line 359

    if repodata.get('_url') != channel_url:

we can be extra cautious that our pickled data logic is in-sync with everything else.

@pde You commented that the `${x:-y}` syntax does not work on non-POSIX busybox:
https://github.com/certbot/certbot/pull/1901#issuecomment-164976573

Does that mean that I should re-write the `${LE_AUTO_SUDO+x}` check too?
